<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite $71 million in U.S. aid since 1978 for a low-income housing project in 
Egypt, it was not until this year that families were able to benefit, according 
to a report by the Agency for International Development. In the report, 
submitted to Congress, AID Inspector General Herbert L. Beckington complained 
about U.S. aid operations as a whole in Egypt, which gets $2.3 billion a year. 
He cited the project near Cairo -- still under construction -- as an example. 
When the project began, the cost was to be shared equally, but by March, 1988, 
the United States had spent $71 million and Egypt $63 million -- and not one 
family had moved in. AID spokesman John Riddle said that since the report was 
written, 205 families have moved in. 
</P>
